# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bokeh-viz
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] In photography, **bokeh** (/ˈboʊkə/ *BOH-kə* or /ˈboʊkeɪ/ *BOH-kay*; Japanese: [boke]) is the aesthetic quality of the blur produced in out-of-focus parts of an image, whether foreground or background or both.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] It is created by using a wide aperture lens.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Some photographers incorrectly restrict use of the term bokeh to the appearance of bright spots in the out-of-focus area caused by circles of confusion.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Bokeh has also been defined as "the way the lens renders out-of-focus points of light".
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Differences in lens aberrations and aperture shape cause very different bokeh effects.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Some lens designs blur the image in a way that is pleasing to the eye, while others produce distracting or unpleasant blurring ("good" and "bad" bokeh, respectively).
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Photographers may deliberately use a shallow focus technique to create images with prominent out-of-focus regions, accentuating their lens's bokeh.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Bokeh is often most visible around small background highlights, such as specular reflections and light sources, which is why it is often associated with such areas.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] However, bokeh is not limited to highlights; blur occurs in all regions of an image which are outside the depth of field.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] The opposite of bokeh—an image in which multiple distances are visible and all are in focus—is deep focus.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] The term comes from the Japanese word *boke* (暈け/ボケ), which means "blur" or "haze", resulting in *boke-aji* (ボケ味), the "blur quality".
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] This is derived as a noun form of the verb *bokeru*, which is written in several ways, with additional meanings and nuances: 暈ける refers to being blurry, hazy or out-of-focus, whereas the 惚ける and 呆ける spellings refer to being mentally hazy, befuddled, childish, senile, or playing stupid.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] *Jisaboke* (時差ボケ) (literally, "time difference fog") is the term for jet lag.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] *Nebokeru* (寝ぼける) is a verb denoting the actions or condition of someone who is half-asleep, or nodding off.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] *Tobokeru* means playing dumb, and *toboketa kao* refers to a poker face.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] The related term *bokashi* (暈かし) means intentional blurring or gradation; that is a noun form of the transitive verb *bokasu* (暈す), which means to make something blurry, rather than to be blurry.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] The spellings *bokeh* and *boke* have both been in use since at least 1996, when Merklinger had suggested "or Bokeh if you prefer." The term *bokeh* has appeared in photography books as early as 1998.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] It is sometimes pronounced /ˈboʊkə/ *BOH-kə*.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Though difficult to quantify, some lenses have subjectively more pleasing out-of-focus areas.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] "Good" bokeh is especially important for macro lenses and long telephoto lenses, because they are typically used in situations that produce shallow depth of field.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Good bokeh is also important for medium telephoto lenses (typically 85–150 mm on 35 mm format).
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] When used in portrait photography (for their "natural" perspective), the photographer usually wants a shallow depth of field, so that the subject stands out sharply against a blurred background.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Bokeh characteristics may be quantified by examining the image's circle of confusion.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] In out-of-focus areas, each point of light becomes an image of the aperture, generally a more or less round disc.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Depending on how a lens is corrected for spherical aberration, the disc may be uniformly illuminated, brighter near the edge, or brighter near the center.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] A well-known lens that exhibited the latter "soap-bubble" characteristic was that produced by Hugo Meyer & Co., more recently revived by Meyer Optik Görlitz.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Lenses that are poorly corrected for spherical aberration will show one kind of disc for out-of-focus points in front of the plane of focus, and a different kind for points behind.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] This may actually be desirable, as blur circles that are dimmer near the edges produce less-defined shapes which blend smoothly with the surrounding image.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] The shape of the aperture has an influence on the subjective quality of bokeh as well.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] For conventional lens designs (with bladed apertures), when a lens is stopped down smaller than its maximum aperture size (minimum f-number), out-of-focus points are blurred into the polygonal shape formed by the aperture blades.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] This is most apparent when a lens produces hard-edged bokeh.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] For this reason, some lenses have many aperture blades and/or blades with curved edges to make the aperture more closely approximate a circle rather than a polygon.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Minolta has been on the forefront of promoting and introducing lenses with near-ideal circular apertures since 1987, but most other manufacturers now offer lenses with shape-optimized diaphragms, at least for the domain of portraiture photography.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] In contrast, a catadioptric telephoto lens renders bokehs resembling doughnuts, because its secondary mirror blocks the central part of the aperture opening.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Recently, photographers have exploited the shape of the bokeh by creating a simple mask out of card with shapes such as hearts or stars, that the photographer wishes the bokeh to be, and placing it over the lens.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Lenses with 11, 12, or 15 blade iris diaphragms are often claimed to excel in bokeh quality.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Because of this, the lenses do not need to reach wide apertures to get better circles (instead of polygons).
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] In the past, wide aperture lenses (f/2, f/2.8) were very expensive, due to the complex mathematical design and manufacturing know-how required, at a time when all computations and glass making were done by hand.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Leica could reach a good bokeh at f/4.5.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Today it is much easier to make an f/1.8 lens, and a 9-bladed lens at f/1.8 is enough for an 85 mm lens to achieve great bokeh.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Some lens manufacturers including Nikon, Minolta, and Sony make lenses designed with specific controls to change the rendering of the out-of-focus areas.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] The Nikon 105 mm DC-Nikkor and 135 mm DC-Nikkor lenses (DC stands for "Defocus Control") have a control ring that permits the overcorrection or undercorrection of spherical aberration to change the bokeh in front of and behind the focal plane.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] The Minolta/Sony STF 135 mm f/2.8 [T4.5] (with STF standing for *smooth trans focus*) is a lens specifically designed to produce pleasing bokeh.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] It is possible to choose between two diaphragms: one with 9 and another with 10 blades.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] An apodization filter is used to soften the aperture edges which results in a smooth defocused area with gradually fading circles.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Those qualities made it the only lens of this kind on the market from its introduction in 1999 to 2014.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] In 2014 Fujifilm announced a lens utilizing a similar apodization filter in the Fujinon XF 56mm F1.2 R APD lens.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Sony added the Sony FE 100 mm F2.8 STF GM OSS in 2017.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] The 'Sigma YS System Focusing' 135 mm f/2.8 also has an extra manually-moved component, intended to compensate for aberration at close-focus distances.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] It can be re-purposed for defocus control.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] In 2015, Meyer Optik USA Inc. launched a Kickstarter campaign to produce the Trioplan f2.9/50, a new lens based on one originally produced by Hugo Meyer & Co.; both lenses exhibit a characteristic "soap-bubble" bokeh.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] The use of anamorphic lenses will cause bokeh to appear differently along the horizontal and vertical axes of the lens, becoming ellipsoidal compared to those in a spherical lens.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] In 2016, Apple Inc. released the iPhone 7 Plus which can take pictures with "Portrait Mode" (a bokeh like effect).
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Samsung's Galaxy Note 8 has a similar effect available.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Both of these phones use dual cameras to detect edges and create a "depth map" of the image, which the phone uses to blur the out-of-focus portions of the photo.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Other phones, like the Google Pixel, only use a single camera and machine learning to create the depth map.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] In 2017, Vivo released a smartphone with dual front lenses for selfies with bokeh.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] The first, a 20 MP lens, uses a 1/2.78" sensor with f/2.0 aperture, while the second, an 8 MP f/2.0 lens, captures depth information.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Bokeh can be made with a combination of both lenses, and shots can be refocused even after they are captured, adding bokeh effects with different depths.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] In early 2018, the Honor 9 Lite smartphone was released with quad cameras (two dual-lens).
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Both the front and back cameras have a 13 MP main lens and a 2 MP lens for capturing bokeh depth information.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Bokeh can be simulated by convolving the image with a kernel that corresponds to the image of an out-of-focus point source taken with a real camera.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Unlike conventional convolution, this convolution has a kernel that depends on the distance of each image point and – at least in principle – has to include image points that are occluded by objects in the foreground.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] To a first approximation, defocus blur is convolution by a uniform disk, a more computationally intensive operation than the "standard" Gaussian blur; the former produces sharp circles around highlights whereas the latter is a much softer effect.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Diffraction may alter the effective shape of the blur.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Some graphics editors have a filter to do this, usually called "Lens Blur".
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Accurate bokeh simulation requires running the blur in linear, HDR space.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] For low dynamic range images, an artificial neural network may be used to reconstruct the HDR light.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] An alternative mechanical mechanism has been proposed for generating bokeh in small aperture cameras such as compacts or cellphone cameras, called image destabilisation, in which both the lens and sensor are moved in order to maintain focus at one focal plane, while defocusing nearby ones.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] This effect currently generates blur in only one axis.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Some advanced digital cameras have bokeh features which take several images with different apertures and focuses and then manually compose them afterward to one image.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] More advanced systems of bokeh use a hardware system of 2 sensors, one sensor to take photo as usual while other ones record depth information.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] Bokeh effect and refocusing can then be applied to an image after the photo is taken.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] In 2009, a research group at MIT Media Lab showed that the bokeh effect can be used to make imperceptibly small barcodes, or bokodes.
[src:bokeh-viz/bokeh] By using barcodes as small as 3 mm with a small lens over them, if the barcode is viewed out of focus through an ordinary camera focused at infinity, the resulting image is large enough to scan the information in the barcode.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] In computer information systems, a **dashboard** is a type of graphical user interface which often provides at-a-glance views of data relevant to a particular objective or process through a combination of visualizations and summary information.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] In other usage, "dashboard" is another name for "progress report" or "report" and is considered a form of data visualization.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] The dashboard is often accessible by a web browser and is typically linked to regularly updating data sources.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are often interactive and facilitate users to explore the data themselves, usually by clicking into elements to view more detailed information.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] The term dashboard originates from the automobile dashboard where drivers monitor the major functions at a glance via the instrument panel.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] The idea of digital dashboards followed the study of decision support systems in the 1970s.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Early predecessors of the modern business dashboard were first developed in the 1980s in the form of Executive Information Systems (EISs).
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Due to problems primarily with data refreshing and handling, it was soon realized that the approach wasn't practical as information was often incomplete, unreliable, and spread across too many disparate sources.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Thus, EISs hibernated until the 1990s when the information age quickened pace and data warehousing, and online analytical processing (OLAP) allowed dashboards to function adequately.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Despite the availability of enabling technologies, the dashboard use didn't become popular until later in that decade, with the rise of key performance indicators (KPIs), and the introduction of Robert S.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] In the late 1990s, Microsoft promoted a concept known as the Digital Nervous System and "digital dashboards" were described as being one leg of that concept.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Today, the use of dashboards forms an important part of Business Performance Management (BPM).
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Initially dashboards were used for monitoring purposes, now with the advancement of technology, dashboards are being used for more analytical purposes.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] The use of dashboards has now been incorporating; scenario analysis, drill down capabilities, and presentation format flexibility.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Digital dashboards allow managers to monitor the contribution of the various departments in their organization.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] In addition, they enable “rolling up” of information to present a consolidated view across an organization.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] To gauge exactly how well an organization is performing overall, digital dashboards allow you to capture and report specific data points from each department within the organization, thus providing a "snapshot" of performance.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Dashboards offers a holistic view of the entire business as it gives the manager a bird's eye view into the performance of sales, data inventory, web traffic, social media analytics and other associated data that is visually presented on a single dashboard.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Dashboards lead to better management of marketing/financial strategies as a dashboard for the display of marketing data makes the process of marketing easier and more reliable as compared to doing it manually.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Web analytics play a crucial role in shaping the marketing strategy of many businesses.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Dashboards also facilitate for better tracking of sales and financial reporting as the data is more precise and in one area.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Lastly, dashboards offer for better customer service through monitoring because they keep both the managers and the clients updated on the project progress through automated emails and notifications.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Dashboards can be broken down according to role and are either strategic, analytical, operational, or informational.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are the 3rd step on the information ladder, demonstrating the conversion of data to increasingly valuable insights.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Strategic dashboards support managers at any level in an organization and provide the quick overview that decision-makers need to monitor the health and opportunities of the business.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Dashboards of this type focus on high-level measures of performance and forecasts.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Strategic dashboards benefit from static snapshots of data (daily, weekly, monthly, and quarterly) that are not constantly changing from one moment to the next.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Dashboards for analytical purposes often include more context, comparisons, and history, along with subtler performance evaluators.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] In addition, analytical dashboards typically support interactions with the data, such as drilling down into the underlying details.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Dashboards for monitoring operations are often designed differently from those that support strategic decision making or data analysis and often require monitoring of activities and events that are constantly changing and might require attention and response at a moment's notice.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Digital dashboards may be laid out to track the flows inherent in the business processes that they monitor.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Graphically, users may see the high-level processes and then drill down into low-level data.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] This level of detail is often buried deep within the corporate enterprise and otherwise unavailable to the senior executives.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Three main types of digital dashboards dominate the market today: desktop software applications, web-browser-based applications, and desktop applications are also known as desktop widgets.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Both Desktop and Browser-based providers enable the distribution of dashboards via a web browser.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] An example of the latter is web-based-browser Asana, which helps teams orchestrate their work, from daily tasks to strategic cross-functional initiatives.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] With it, teams can manage everything from company objectives to digital transformation to product launches and marketing campaigns.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Specialized dashboards may track all corporate functions.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Examples include human resources, recruiting, sales, operations, security, information technology, project management, customer relationship management, digital marketing and many more departmental dashboards.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] For a smaller organization like a startup a compact startup scorecard dashboard tracks important activities across lot of domains ranging from social media to sales.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Digital dashboard projects involve business units as the driver and the information technology department as the enabler.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Therefore, the success of dashboard projects depends on the relevancy/importance of information provided within the dashboard.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] This includes the metrics chosen to monitor and the timeliness of the data forming those metrics; data must be up to date and accurate.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Key performance indicators, balanced scorecards, and sales performance figures are some of the content appropriate on business dashboards.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Dashboards involve the combination of visual and functional features.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] This combination of features helps improve cognition and interpretation.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] A performance dashboard sits at the intersection of two powerful disciplines: business intelligence and performance management.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Therefore, there are different users who could use these dashboards for different reasons.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] For example, a level of workers could look at monitoring inventory while those in more managerial roles can look at lagging measure.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Then executives could utilize the dashboard to evaluate strategic performance against objectives.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Balanced scorecards and dashboards have been linked together as if they were interchangeable.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] However, although both visually display critical information, the difference is in the format: Scorecards can open the quality of an operation while dashboards provide calculated direction.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] A balanced scorecard has what they called a "prescriptive" format.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Each of these sections ensures that a Balanced Scorecard is essentially connected to the businesses critical strategic needs.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] The design of a dashboard is more loosely defined.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are usually a series of graphics, charts, gauges and other visual indicators that can be monitored and interpreted.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Even when there is a strategic link, on a dashboard, it may not be noticed as such since objectives are not normally present on dashboards.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] However, dashboards can be customized to link their graphs and charts to strategic objectives.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Digital dashboard technology is available "out-of-the-box" from many software providers.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Some companies, however, continue to do in-house development and maintenance of dashboard applications.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] For example, GE Aviation has developed a proprietary software/portal called "Digital Cockpit" to monitor the trends in the aircraft spare parts business.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] A good information design will clearly communicate key information to users and makes supporting information easily accessible.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] There are a few key elements to a good dashboard:.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] A research-based framework for Business Intelligence dashboard design suggests that "cross-visual interactivity" is the most impactful of all features.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Dashboards serve as a visual representation for a company to monitor progress and trends, not only among themselves but against other companies as well.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Dashboards and visualizations contain data that is updated in real time.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] For example, if the underlying data in an Excel spreadsheet were to change, so would the visualization.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Power BI provides the tools for a user to create different types of visualizations to communicate the data that they are using.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Some examples of these visualizations include graphs, maps, and clustered columns.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Power BI pulls data from Excel that can be used to create dashboards and visualizations.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Whereas Excel does not import data from Power BI.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Excel is typically used for less data and Power BI is more complex.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Power BI can be used to display trends over time.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] For example, a company can create a time plot that shows its costs and revenues over a certain period.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] The data can then be arranged to show per day, month, quarter, year, etc.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] This requires simple formatting tools so the data can quickly be changed and compared.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Power BI allows the user to customize their visualizations by adding colors and labels.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] In addition, when the user clicks a data point, they are able to understand what the point or selection is showing.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Power BI also has a commonly used map feature where businesses can view their sales and earnings across different states and countries.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Places with the highest amounts of data will appear larger in size.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] For example, a state with the most revenue will be bigger than states with less data.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Power BI is also interactive in that in any type of map a person can expand a specific category to look deeper into the data contained.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Tableau is another program that allows users to create dashboards.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Allegedly, One of Tableau's biggest advantages is how much data it can hold.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Tableau can hold an unlimited amount, whereas an Excel spreadsheet has a capacity of 1,048,576 rows.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] However, it is possible to hold and analyze effectively billions of rows in Excel, using its Power Pivot feature.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Tableau has the ability to make interactive dashboards by clicking into a specific point.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] For example, you can have data be displayed within a map.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] By clicking a specific state or city you can get a closer look at the data contained within that location.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Filters and parameters can also be added.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] For example, if one were to analyze revenues across the United States you could set a parameter to only show salaries within a particular range.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Once set, only states within this range will be highlighted.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Excel has many tools that help the user not only implement data but also visualize data.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Excel has many built in functions that can help break down data and also separate data by scenarios.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] The user can easily download and add files to their Excel sheets to use for their data.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Other tools Excel offers is the use of conditional formatting and basic pivot tables and charts.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Excel allows the user to reference other cells which ultimately allows for complex computations to be made and conclusions to be drawn from data.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] There are certain guidelines that can be useful when creating dashboards and other visualizations.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] The guidelines have a structure that can be followed and that is beginning with reading direction.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] When it comes to how you are arranging your information on your dashboard or a visualization it can be helpful to think about reading direction.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] General reading direction is from left to right and from top to bottom.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Having information flow in this structure will allow others to read and understand your visuals in a more natural structure.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Local proximity is another idea to keep in mind when creating a visual or a dashboard.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Having information in a close proximity can be compared with a better effectiveness and allow users to draw conclusions.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Being able to make sure the user is not being overloaded with information when creating your visual.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Having a few key figures with significant importance can be more helpful compared to having too much information.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] When you have too much information and not a structure to what you are presenting then that is known as a “data graveyard”.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Another aspect to keep in mind while creating visuals that goes along with information overload is the idea of interaction within your visual.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Interacting with the dashboard would allow for further detail to be obtained from the user and allow them to better understand the information on your dashboard.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Chart visualization is an important aspect when creating dashboards, diagrams in particular.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] When you have complex data it can be difficult to come to conclusions from that material and being able to have different visual elements within the dashboard can be helpful in giving a larger overview of the material.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Being able to have a visual reporting system allows multiple processing operations to be carried out and that could increase the effectiveness of decisions.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] There are different types of visualizations that can be seen as more effective depending on the data type and the recipient.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Looking at traditional business graphics in an interactive form is another aspect to keep in mind when creating a dashboard.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Business charts are used mainly in the form of interactive dashboards.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] A major advantage of business charts is that the majority of users have an understanding of them.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] There are many connections between dashboards and accounting.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Dashboards aid with budgeting, management control, and wage control.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are used to present data in a quick and easy to read way.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] The ability to present data in a quick way with a visual allows for more data to be processed and understood.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are used for performance reports, sales analysis on sectors, and inventory rotation.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Dashboards should be quick visualizations that allow decisions to be made quicker than they usually would without the access to dashboard technology.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are also used in accounting decision making settings.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] The data can help prove a change is efficient or inefficient and therefore help with improving systems throughout an organization.
[src:bokeh-viz/dashboard-computing] In order for a dashboard to be efficient, the individual creating the dashboard needs to make sure that the information is simple and easy to read and be interpreted.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] In addition, **Narrative visualization** is a method that uses visual elements such as charts, graphs, maps and the like to convey data or information.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] This approach blends data analysis, storytelling, and visualization to present information through structured narrative flows- *using visuals not just to present statistics, but to tell a story through data*.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Its goal is to help people identify trends, patterns, and relationships in data through a compelling story-driven visual experience.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Emerging technologies like virtual, augmented and mixed reality have the potential to make information visualization more immersive, intuitive, interactive and easily manipulable and thus enhance the user's visual perception and cognition.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Effective data visualization is well-sourced, appropriately contextualized, and presented in a simple, uncluttered manner.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The underlying data is accurate and up-to-date to ensure insights are reliable.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Graphical items are well-chosen and aesthetically appealing, with shapes, colors and other visual elements used deliberately in a meaningful and non-distracting manner.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The visuals are accompanied by supporting texts.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Verbal and graphical components complement each other to ensure clear, quick and memorable understanding.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Effective information visualization is aware of the needs and expertise level of the target audience.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data scientists, analysts and data mining specialists use data visualization to check data quality, find errors, unusual gaps, missing values, clean data, explore the structures and features of data, and assess outputs of data-driven models.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization can be part of *data storytelling*, where they are paired with a narrative structure, to contextualize the analyzed data and communicate insights gained from analyzing it to convince the audience into making a decision or taking action.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization is interdisciplinary, it incorporates principles found in descriptive statistics, visual communication, graphic design, cognitive science and, interactive computer graphics and human-computer interaction.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Since effective visualization requires design skills, statistical skills and computing skills, it is both an art and a science.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Visual analytics combines statistical data analysis, data and information visualization, and human analytical reasoning through interactive visual interfaces to help users reach conclusions, gain actionable insights and make informed decisions which are otherwise difficult for computers to do.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Research into how people read and misread types of visualizations helps to determine what types and features of visualizations are most understandable and effective.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Unintentionally poor or intentionally misleading and deceptive visualizations can function as powerful tools which disseminate misinformation, manipulate public perception and divert public opinion.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Thus data visualization literacy has become an important component of data and information literacy in the information age akin to the roles played by textual, mathematical and visual literacy in the past.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The field of data and information visualization has emerged "from research in human–computer interaction, computer science, graphics, visual design, psychology, photography and business methods.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] It is increasingly applied as a critical component in scientific research, digital libraries, data mining, financial data analysis, market studies, manufacturing production control, and drug discovery".
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization presumes that "visual representations and interaction techniques take advantage of the human eye's broad bandwidth pathway into the mind to allow users to see, explore, and understand large amounts of information at once.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data analysis is an indispensable part of all applied research and problem solving in industry.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Among these approaches, information visualization, or visual data analysis, is the most reliant on the cognitive skills of human analysts, and allows the discovery of unstructured actionable insights that are limited only by human imagination and creativity.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The analyst does not have to learn any sophisticated methods to be able to interpret the visualizations of the data.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Information visualization is also a hypothesis generation scheme, which can be, and is typically followed by more analytical or formal analysis, such as statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] To communicate information clearly and efficiently, data visualization uses statistical graphics, plots, information graphics and other tools.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Numerical data may be encoded using dots, lines, or bars, to visually communicate a quantitative message.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Effective visualization helps users analyze and reason about data and evidence.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] It makes complex data more accessible, understandable, and usable, but can also be reductive.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Users may have particular analytical tasks, such as making comparisons or understanding causality, and the design principle of the graphic (i.e., showing comparisons or showing causality) follows the task.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Tables are generally used where users will look up a specific measurement, while charts of various types are used to show patterns or relationships in the data for one or more variables.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization refers to the techniques used to communicate data or information by encoding it as visual objects (e.g., points, lines, or bars) contained in graphics.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The goal is to communicate information clearly and efficiently to users.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] It is one of the steps in data analysis or data science.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] According to Vitaly Friedman (2008) the "main goal of data visualization is to communicate information clearly and effectively through graphical means.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] It doesn't mean that data visualization needs to look boring to be functional or extremely sophisticated to look beautiful.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] To convey ideas effectively, both aesthetic form and functionality need to go hand in hand, providing insights into a rather sparse and complex data set by communicating its key aspects in a more intuitive way.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Yet designers often fail to achieve a balance between form and function, creating gorgeous data visualizations which fail to serve their main purpose — to communicate information".
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Wattenberg suggested that an ideal visualization should not only communicate clearly, but stimulate viewer engagement and attention.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is closely related to information graphics, information visualization, scientific visualization, exploratory data analysis and statistical graphics.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] In the new millennium, data visualization has become an active area of research, teaching and development.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] (2002), it has united scientific and information visualization.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] In the commercial environment data visualization is often referred to as dashboards.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Infographics are another very common form of data visualization.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Edward Tufte has explained that users of information displays are executing particular *analytical tasks* such as making comparisons.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The *design principle* of the information graphic should support the analytical task.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] As William Cleveland and Robert McGill show, different graphical elements accomplish this more or less effectively.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, dot plots and bar charts outperform pie charts.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] In his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, Edward Tufte defines 'graphical displays' and principles for effective graphical display in the following passage: "Excellence in statistical graphics consists of complex ideas communicated with clarity, precision, and efficiency.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, the Minard diagram shows the losses suffered by Napoleon's army in the 1812–1813 period.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Six variables are plotted: the size of the army, its location on a two-dimensional surface (x and y), time, the direction of movement, and temperature.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The line width illustrates a comparison (size of the army at points in time), while the temperature axis suggests a cause of the change in army size.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] This multivariate display on a two-dimensional surface tells a story that can be grasped immediately while identifying the source data to build credibility.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Not applying these principles may result in misleading graphs, distorting the message, or supporting an erroneous conclusion.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] According to Tufte, chartjunk refers to the extraneous interior decoration of the graphic that does not enhance the message or gratuitous three-dimensional or perspective effects.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Needlessly separating the explanatory key from the image itself, requiring the eye to travel back and forth from the image to the key, is a form of "administrative debris." The ratio of "data to ink" should be maximized, erasing non-data ink where feasible.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The Congressional Budget Office summarized several best practices for graphical displays in a June 2014 presentation.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] These included: a) Knowing your audience; b) Designing graphics that can stand alone outside the report's context; and c) Designing graphics that communicate the key messages in the report.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] For greatest efficiency and simplicity of design and user experience, this readability is enhanced through the use of bijective mapping in that design of the image elements - where the mapping of representational element to data variable is unique.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Kosara (2007) also identifies the need for a visualisation to be "recognisable as a visualisation and not appear to be something else".
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] He also states that recognisability and readability may not always be required in all types of visualisation e.g.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] "informative art" (which would still meet all three above criteria but might not look like a visualisation) or "artistic visualisation" (which similarly is still based on non-visual data to create an image, but may not be readable or recognisable).
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Ranking: Categorical subdivisions are ranked in ascending or descending order, such as a ranking of sales performance (the *measure*) by sales persons (the *category*, with each sales person a *categorical subdivision*) during a single period.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used to show the comparison across the sales persons.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Part-to-whole: Categorical subdivisions are measured as a ratio to the whole (i.e., a percentage out of 100%).
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] A pie chart or bar chart can show the comparison of ratios, such as the market share represented by competitors in a market.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Deviation: Categorical subdivisions are compared against a reference, such as a comparison of actual vs. budget expenses for several departments of a business for a given time period.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart can show comparison of the actual versus the reference amount.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Frequency distribution: Shows the number of observations of a particular variable for given interval, such as the number of years in which the stock market return is between intervals such as 0–10%, 11–20%, etc.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] A histogram, a type of bar chart, may be used for this analysis.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] A boxplot helps visualize key statistics about the distribution, such as median, quartiles, outliers, etc.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Correlation: Comparison between observations represented by two variables (X,Y) to determine if they tend to move in the same or opposite directions.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, plotting unemployment (X) and inflation (Y) for a sample of months.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] A scatter plot is typically used for this message.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Nominal comparison: Comparing categorical subdivisions in no particular order, such as the sales volume by product code.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used for this comparison.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Geographic or geospatial: Comparison of a variable across a map or layout, such as the unemployment rate by state or the number of persons on the various floors of a building.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Analysts reviewing a set of data may consider whether some or all of the messages and graphic types above are applicable to their task and audience.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The process of trial and error to identify meaningful relationships and messages in the data is part of exploratory data analysis.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] A human can distinguish differences in line length, shape, orientation, distances, and color (hue) readily without significant processing effort; these are referred to as "pre-attentive attributes".
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, it may require significant time and effort ("attentive processing") to identify the number of times the digit "5" appears in a series of numbers; but if that digit is different in size, orientation, or color, instances of the digit can be noted quickly through pre-attentive processing.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Compelling graphics take advantage of pre-attentive processing and attributes and the relative strength of these attributes.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, since humans can more easily process differences in line length than surface area, it may be more effective to use a bar chart (which takes advantage of line length to show comparison) rather than pie charts (which use surface area to show comparison).
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Almost all data visualizations are created for human consumption.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Knowledge of human perception and cognition is necessary when designing intuitive visualizations.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Cognition refers to processes in human beings like perception, attention, learning, memory, thought, concept formation, reading, and problem solving.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Human visual processing is efficient in detecting changes and making comparisons between quantities, sizes, shapes and variations in lightness.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] When properties of symbolic data are mapped to visual properties, humans can browse through large amounts of data efficiently.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] It is estimated that 2/3 of the brain's neurons can be involved in visual processing.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Proper visualization provides a different approach to show potential connections, relationships, etc. which are not as obvious in non-visualized quantitative data.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Visualization can become a means of data exploration.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Studies have shown individuals used on average 19% less cognitive resources, and 4.5% better able to recall details when comparing data visualization with text.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] There is no comprehensive history of data visualization.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] There are no accounts that span the entire development of visual thinking and visual representation of data, and which collate the contributions of disparate disciplines.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Michael Friendly and Daniel Denis of York University are engaged in a project that attempts to provide a comprehensive history of visualization.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is not a modern development.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Since prehistory, stellar data, or information such as location of stars were visualized on the walls of caves (such as those found in Lascaux Cave in Southern France) since the Pleistocene era.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Physical artefacts such as Mesopotamian clay tokens (5500 BC), Inca quipus (2600 BC) and Marshall Islands stick charts (n.d.) can also be considered as visualizing quantitative information.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The first documented data visualization can be tracked back to 1160 B.C. with the Turin Papyrus Map which accurately illustrates the distribution of geological resources and provides information about quarrying of those resources.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Such maps can be categorized as thematic cartography, which is a type of data visualization that presents and communicates specific data and information through a geographical illustration designed to show a particular theme connected with a specific geographic area.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Earliest documented forms of data visualization were various thematic maps from different cultures and ideograms and hieroglyphs that provided and allowed interpretation of information illustrated.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, Linear B tablets of Mycenae provided a visualization of information regarding Late Bronze Age era trades in the Mediterranean.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The idea of coordinates was used by ancient Egyptian surveyors in laying out towns, earthly and heavenly positions were located by something akin to latitude and longitude at least by 200 BC, and the map projection of a spherical Earth into latitude and longitude by Claudius Ptolemy [c.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] 165] in Alexandria would serve as reference standards until the 14th century.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The invention of paper and parchment allowed further development of visualizations.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] One graph from the 10th or possibly 11th century is an illustration of planetary movements, used in an appendix of a textbook in monastery schools.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The graph apparently was meant to represent a plot of the inclinations of the planetary orbits as a function of the time.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] For this purpose, the zone of the zodiac was represented on a plane with a horizontal line divided into thirty parts as the time or longitudinal axis.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The vertical axis designates the width of the zodiac.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The horizontal scale appears to have been chosen for each planet individually for the periods cannot be reconciled.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The accompanying text refers only to the amplitudes.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The curves are apparently not related in time.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] By the 16th century, techniques and instruments for precise observation and measurement of physical quantities, and geographic and celestial position were well-developed (for example, a "wall quadrant" constructed by Tycho Brahe [1546–1601], covering an entire wall in his observatory).
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Particularly important were the development of triangulation and other methods to determine mapping locations accurately.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Very early, the measure of time led scholars to develop innovative way of visualizing the data (e.g.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Lorenz Codomann in 1596, Johannes Temporarius in 1596).
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Mathematicians René Descartes and Pierre de Fermat developed analytic geometry and two-dimensional coordinate system which heavily influenced the practical methods of displaying and calculating values.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Fermat and Blaise Pascal's work on statistics and probability theory laid the groundwork for what we now conceptualize as data.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] These developments helped William Playfair, who saw potential for graphical communication of quantitative data, to generate and develop graphical methods of statistics.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] In 1786, Playfair published the first presentation graphics.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Jacques Bertin used quantitative graphs to represent information "intuitively, clearly, accurately, and efficiently".
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] John Tukey and Edward Tufte pushed the bounds of data visualization; Tukey with his new statistical approach of exploratory data analysis and Tufte with his book "The Visual Display of Quantitative Information" paved the way for refining data visualization techniques for more than statisticians.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] With the progression of technology came the progression of data visualization; starting with hand-drawn visualizations and evolving into more technical applications – including interactive designs leading to software visualization.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The modern study of visualization started with computer graphics, which "has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] However, in its early days the lack of graphics power often limited its usefulness.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the special issue of Computer Graphics on Visualization in *Scientific Computing*.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Since then there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH".
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] They have been devoted to the general topics of data visualization, information visualization and scientific visualization, and more specific areas such as volume visualization.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Programs like SAS, SOFA, R, Minitab, Cornerstone and more allow for data visualization in the field of statistics.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Other data visualization applications, more focused and unique to individuals, programming languages such as D3, Python (through matplotlib, seaborn) and JavaScript and Java(through JavaFX) help to make the visualization of quantitative data a possibility.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Private schools have also developed programs to meet the demand for learning data visualization and associated programming libraries, including free programs like The Data Incubator or paid programs like General Assembly.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Beginning with the symposium "Data to Discovery" in 2013, ArtCenter College of Design, Caltech and JPL in Pasadena have run an annual program on interactive data visualization.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The program asks: How can interactive data visualization help scientists and engineers explore their data more effectively?
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] How can computing, design, and design thinking help maximize research results?
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] What methodologies are most effective for leveraging knowledge from these fields?
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] In recent years, with the increasing popularity of games, data and information visualization has been gradually applied in the gaming industry through the use of analytical tools to assess player statistics and game performance, which are visualized in the form of health points, maps, and diagrams.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The data is then collected and stored by developers.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The implementation of these tools in gaming assists developers in improving user experience and in the development and updating of newer games.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization involves specific terminology, some of which is derived from statistics.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The distinction between quantitative and categorical variables is important because the two types require different methods of visualization.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Two primary types of information displays are tables and graphs.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Eppler and Lengler have developed the "Periodic Table of Visualization Methods," an interactive chart displaying various data visualization methods.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] It includes six types of data visualization methods: data, information, concept, strategy, metaphor and compound.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Interactive data visualization has been a pursuit of statisticians since the late 1960s.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Examples of the developments can be found on the American Statistical Association video lending library.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] There are different approaches on the scope of data visualization.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] One common focus is on information presentation, such as Friedman (2008).
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Friendly (2008) presumes two main parts of data visualization: statistical graphics, and thematic cartography.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] All these subjects are closely related to graphic design and information representation.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Within The Harvard Business Review, Scott Berinato developed a framework to approach data visualisation.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] To start thinking visually, users must consider two questions; 1) What you have and 2) what you're doing.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] The first step is identifying what data you want visualised.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] It is data-driven like profit over the past ten years or a conceptual idea like how a specific organisation is structured.
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Once this question is answered one can then focus on whether they are trying to communicate information (declarative visualisation) or trying to figure something out (exploratory visualisation).
[src:bokeh-viz/data-visualization-p01] Scott Berinato combines these questions to give four types of visual communication that each have their own goals.
[src:bokeh-viz/first-steps] Bokeh is officially supported and tested on Python 3.10 and above (CPython).
[src:bokeh-viz/first-steps] Conda requires either Anaconda or Miniconda to be installed on your system.
[src:bokeh-viz/first-steps] For more detailed information on installing and potential problems you might encounter, go to the Installation details section.
[src:bokeh-viz/first-steps] Follow these guides to quickly learn about the most important features and capabilities of Bokeh.
[src:bokeh-viz/first-steps] The first steps guides are for anybody who is new to Bokeh.
[src:bokeh-viz/first-steps] The only prerequisites for using these guides are a basic understanding of Python and a working installation of Bokeh.
[src:bokeh-viz/first-steps] The first steps guides include lots of examples that you can copy to your development environment.
[src:bokeh-viz/first-steps] There are also many links to the more in-depth resources of the user guide and reference guide in case you want to learn more about any of the topics covered in the first steps guides.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Visualization today has ever-expanding applications in science, education, engineering (e.g., product visualization), interactive multimedia, medicine, etc.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Typical of a visualization application is the field of computer graphics.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] The invention of computer graphics (and 3D computer graphics) may be the most important development in visualization since the invention of central perspective in the Renaissance period.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] The development of animation also helped advance visualization.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] The use of visualization to present information is not a new phenomenon.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] It has been used in maps, scientific drawings, and data plots for over a thousand years.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Examples from cartography include Ptolemy's Geographia (2nd century AD), a map of China (1137 AD), and Minard's map (1861) of Napoleon's invasion of Russia a century and a half ago.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Most of the concepts learned in devising these images carry over in a straightforward manner to computer visualization.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Edward Tufte has written three critically acclaimed books that explain many of these principles.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Computer graphics has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the publication of Visualization in Scientific Computing, a special issue of Computer Graphics.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Since then, there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH, devoted to the general topic, and special areas in the field, for example volume visualization.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Most people are familiar with the digital animations produced to present meteorological data during weather reports on television, though few can distinguish between those models of reality and the satellite photos that are also shown on such programs.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] TV also offers scientific visualizations when it shows computer drawn and animated reconstructions of road or airplane accidents.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Some of the most popular examples of scientific visualizations are computer-generated images that show real spacecraft in action, out in the void far beyond Earth, or on other planets.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Dynamic forms of visualization, such as educational animation or timelines, have the potential to enhance learning about systems that change over time.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Apart from the distinction between interactive visualizations and animation, the most useful categorization is probably between abstract and model-based scientific visualizations.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] The abstract visualizations show completely conceptual constructs in 2D or 3D.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] These generated shapes are completely arbitrary.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] The model-based visualizations either place overlays of data on real or digitally constructed images of reality or make a digital construction of a real object directly from the scientific data.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Scientific visualization is usually done with specialized software, though there are a few exceptions, noted below.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Some of these specialized programs have been released as open source software, having very often its origins in universities, within an academic environment where sharing software tools and giving access to the source code is common.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] There are also many proprietary software packages of scientific visualization tools.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Models and frameworks for building visualizations include the data flow models popularized by systems such as AVS, IRIS Explorer, and VTK toolkit, and data state models in spreadsheet systems such as the Spreadsheet for Visualization and Spreadsheet for Images.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] As a subject in computer science, scientific visualization is the use of interactive, sensory representations, typically visual, of abstract data to reinforce cognition, hypothesis building, and reasoning.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Scientific visualization is the transformation, selection, or representation of data from simulations or experiments, with an implicit or explicit geometric structure, to allow the exploration, analysis, and understanding of the data.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Scientific visualization focuses and emphasizes the representation of higher order data using primarily graphics and animation techniques.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] It is a very important part of visualization and maybe the first one, as the visualization of experiments and phenomena is as old as science itself.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Traditional areas of scientific visualization are flow visualization, medical visualization, astrophysical visualization, and chemical visualization.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] There are several different techniques to visualize scientific data, with isosurface reconstruction and direct volume rendering being the more common.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Data visualization is a related subcategory of visualization dealing with statistical graphics and geospatial data (as in thematic cartography) that is abstracted in schematic form.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Information visualization concentrates on the use of computer-supported tools to explore large amount of abstract data.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] The term "information visualization" was originally coined by the User Interface Research Group at Xerox PARC and included Jock Mackinlay.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Practical application of information visualization in computer programs involves selecting, transforming, and representing abstract data in a form that facilitates human interaction for exploration and understanding.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Important aspects of information visualization are dynamics of visual representation and the interactivity.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Strong techniques enable the user to modify the visualization in real-time, thus affording unparalleled perception of patterns and structural relations in the abstract data in question.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Educational visualization is using a simulation to create an image of something so it can be taught about.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] This is very useful when teaching about a topic that is difficult to otherwise see, for example, atomic structure, because atoms are far too small to be studied easily without expensive and difficult to use scientific equipment.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] The use of visual representations to transfer knowledge between at least two persons aims to improve the transfer of knowledge by using computer and non-computer-based visualization methods complementarily.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Thus properly designed visualization is an important part of not only data analysis but knowledge transfer process, too.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Knowledge transfer may be significantly improved using hybrid designs as it enhances information density but may decrease clarity as well.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] For example, visualization of a 3D scalar field may be implemented using iso-surfaces for field distribution and textures for the gradient of the field.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Examples of such visual formats are sketches, diagrams, images, objects, interactive visualizations, information visualization applications, and imaginary visualizations as in stories.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] While information visualization concentrates on the use of computer-supported tools to derive new insights, knowledge visualization focuses on transferring insights and creating new knowledge in groups.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Beyond the mere transfer of facts, knowledge visualization aims to further transfer insights, experiences, attitudes, values, expectations, perspectives, opinions, and estimates in different fields by using various complementary visualizations.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Product visualization involves visualization software technology for the viewing and manipulation of 3D models, technical drawing and other related documentation of manufactured components and large assemblies of products.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] It is a key part of product lifecycle management.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Product visualization software typically provides high levels of photorealism so that a product can be viewed before it is actually manufactured.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] This supports functions ranging from design and styling to sales and marketing.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] *Technical visualization* is an important aspect of product development.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Originally technical drawings were made by hand, but with the rise of advanced computer graphics the drawing board has been replaced by computer-aided design (CAD).
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] CAD-drawings and models have several advantages over hand-made drawings such as the possibility of 3-D modeling, rapid prototyping, and simulation.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] 3D product visualization promises more interactive experiences for online shoppers, but also challenges retailers to overcome hurdles in the production of 3D content, as large-scale 3D content production can be extremely costly and time-consuming.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] In recent years, product visualization has increasingly incorporated interactive and real-time technologies, particularly in e-commerce environments.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Modern 3D visualization tools enable users to explore products in detail, customize attributes such as color, materials, and configuration, and view items in simulated or real-world contexts.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] These capabilities enhance user engagement and support more informed decision-making by providing realistic and context-aware representations of products.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] As a result, product visualization can help reduce uncertainty prior to purchase and contribute to lower product return rates.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Visual communication is the communication of ideas through the visual display of information.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Primarily associated with two dimensional images, it includes: alphanumerics, art, signs, and electronic resources.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Recent research in the field has focused on web design and graphically oriented usability.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Visual analytics focuses on human interaction with visualization systems as part of a larger process of data analysis.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Visual analytics has been defined as "the science of analytical reasoning supported by the interactive visual interface".
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Its focus is on human information discourse (interaction) within massive, dynamically changing information spaces.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Visual analytics research concentrates on support for perceptual and cognitive operations that enable users to detect the expected and discover the unexpected in complex information spaces.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Technologies resulting from visual analytics find their application in almost all fields, but are being driven by critical needs (and funding) in biology and national security.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] One particular type of interactive visualization is virtual reality (VR), where the visual representation of information is presented using an immersive display device such as a stereo projector (see stereoscopy).
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Another type of interactive visualization is collaborative visualization, in which multiple people interact with the same computer visualization to communicate their ideas to each other or to explore information cooperatively.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Frequently, collaborative visualization is used when people are physically separated.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Using several networked computers, the same visualization can be presented to each person simultaneously.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] The people then make annotations to the visualization as well as communicate via audio (i.e., telephone), video (i.e., a video-conference), or text (i.e., IRC) messages.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] The Programmer's Hierarchical Interactive Graphics System (PHIGS) was one of the first programmatic efforts at interactive visualization and provided an enumeration of the types of input humans provide.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] All of these actions require a physical device.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Input devices range from the common – keyboards, mice, graphics tablets, trackballs, and touchpads – to the esoteric – wired gloves, boom arms, and even omnidirectional treadmills.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] These input actions can be used to control both the unique information being represented or the way that the information is presented.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] When the information being presented is altered, the visualization is usually part of a feedback loop.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] For example, consider an aircraft avionics system where the pilot inputs roll, pitch, and yaw and the visualization system provides a rendering of the aircraft's new attitude.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Another example would be a scientist who changes a simulation while it is running in response to a visualization of its current progress.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] This is called *computational steering*.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] More frequently, the representation of the information is changed rather than the information itself.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Experiments have shown that a delay of more than 20 ms between when input is provided and a visual representation is updated is noticeable by most people .
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Thus it is desirable for an interactive visualization to provide a rendering based on human input within this time frame.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] However, when large amounts of data must be processed to create a visualization, this becomes hard or even impossible with current technology.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Thus the term "interactive visualization" is usually applied to systems that provide feedback to users within several seconds of input.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] The term *interactive framerate* is often used to measure how interactive a visualization is.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Framerates measure the frequency with which an image (a frame) can be generated by a visualization system.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] A framerate of 50 frames per second (frame/s) is considered good while 0.1 frame/s would be considered poor.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] The use of framerates to characterize interactivity is slightly misleading however, since framerate is a measure of bandwidth while humans are more sensitive to latency.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Specifically, it is possible to achieve a good framerate of 50 frame/s but if the images generated refer to changes to the visualization that a person made more than 1 second ago, it will not feel interactive to a person.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] The rapid response time required for interactive visualization is a difficult constraint to meet and there are several approaches that have been explored to provide people with rapid visual feedback based on their input.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] *Progressive rendering* – where a framerate is guaranteed by rendering some subset of the information to be presented and providing incremental (progressive) improvements to the rendering once the visualization is no longer changing.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] *Level-of-detail (LOD) rendering* – where simplified representations of information are rendered to achieve a desired framerate while a person is providing input and then the full representation is used to generate a still image once the person is through manipulating the visualization.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] Subsampling can also be used to accelerate rendering techniques such as volume visualization that require more than twice the computations for an image twice the size.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] By rendering a smaller image and then scaling the image to fill the requested screen space, much less time is required to render the same data.
[src:bokeh-viz/interactive-visualization] *Frameless rendering* – where the visualization is no longer presented as a time series of images, but as a single image where different regions are updated over time.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] A **web browser**, often abbreviated as **browser**, is an application for accessing websites.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] When a user requests a web page from a particular website, the browser retrieves its files from a web server and then displays the page on the user's screen.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Browsers can also display content stored locally on the user's device.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Browsers are used on a range of devices, including desktops, laptops, tablets, smartphones, smartwatches, smart televisions and consoles.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] As of 2026, the most used browsers worldwide are Google Chrome (~69% market share), Safari (~16%), Edge (~5%), Firefox (~2%), Samsung Browser (~2%), and Opera (~2%).
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] As of 2023, an estimated 5.4 billion people had used a browser.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] The purpose of a web browser is to fetch content and display it on the user's device.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] This process begins when the user inputs a Uniform Resource Locator (URL), such as *`https://en.wikipedia.org/`*, into the browser's address bar.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Virtually all URLs on the Web start with either *`http:`* or *`https:`* which means they are retrieved with the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP).
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] For secure mode (HTTPS), the connection between the browser and web server is encrypted, providing a secure and private data transfer.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] For this reason, a web browser is often referred to as an HTTP client or a user agent.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Requisite materials, including text, style sheets, images, and other types of multimedia, are downloaded from the server.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Once the materials have been downloaded, the web browser's engine (also known as a layout engine or rendering engine) is responsible for converting those resources into an interactive visual representation of the page on the user's device.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Modern web browsers also contain separate JavaScript engines which enable more complex interactive applications inside the browser.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] A web browser that does not render a graphical user interface is known as a headless browser.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Web pages usually contain hyperlinks to other pages and resources.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Each link contains a URL, and when it is clicked or tapped, the browser navigates to the new resource.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Most browsers use an internal cache of web page resources to improve loading times for subsequent visits to the same page.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] The cache can store many items, such as large images, so they do not need to be downloaded from the server again.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Cached items are usually only stored for as long as the web server stipulates in its HTTP response messages.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] A web browser is not the same thing as a search engine, though the two are often confused.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] A search engine is a website that provides links to other websites and allows users to search for specific resources using a textual query.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] However, web browsers are often used to access search engines, and most modern browsers allow users to access a default search engine directly by typing a query into the address bar.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] The first web browser, called WorldWideWeb, was created in 1990 by Sir Tim Berners-Lee.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] He then recruited Nicola Pellow to write the Line Mode Browser, which displayed web pages on dumb terminals.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] The Mosaic web browser was released in April 1993, and was later credited as the first web browser to find mainstream popularity.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Its innovative graphical user interface made the World Wide Web easy to navigate and thus more accessible to the average person.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] This, in turn, sparked the Internet boom of the 1990s, when the Web grew at a very rapid rate.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released the Mosaic-influenced Netscape Navigator in 1994.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Navigator quickly became the most popular browser.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Within a few years, Microsoft gained a dominant position in the browser market for two reasons: it bundled Internet Explorer with its popular Windows operating system and did so as freeware with no restrictions on usage.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] The market share of Internet Explorer peaked at over 95% in the early 2000s.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] In 1998, Netscape launched what would become the Mozilla Foundation to create a new browser using the open-source software model.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] This work evolved into the Firefox browser, first released by Mozilla in 2004.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Firefox's market share peaked at 32% in 2010.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Apple released its Safari browser in 2003; it remains the dominant browser on Apple devices, though it did not become popular elsewhere.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, which steadily took market share from Internet Explorer and became the most popular browser in 2012.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Chrome has remained dominant ever since.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] In 2015, Microsoft replaced Internet Explorer with Edge [Legacy] for the Windows 10 release.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] In 2020, this legacy version was replaced by a new Chromium-based version of Edge.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Since the early 2000s, browsers have greatly expanded their HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and multimedia capabilities.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] One reason has been to enable more sophisticated websites, such as web apps.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Another factor is the significant increase of broadband connectivity in many parts of the world, enabling people to access data-intensive content, such as streaming HD video on YouTube, that was not possible during the era of dial-up modems.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Starting in the mid-2020s, browsers with integrated artificial intelligence (AI) capabilities, known as AI browsers, have become increasingly common.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] This includes both new entrants to the browser market, such as Perplexity Comet and ChatGPT Atlas, and established browsers that added AI features, such as Chrome with the Gemini chatbot and Edge with the Copilot chatbot.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] The most popular browsers share many features.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] They automatically log users' browsing history, unless the users turn off their browsing history or use the non-logging private mode.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] They also allow users to set bookmarks, customize the browser with extensions, and manage their downloads and passwords.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Some provide a sync service and web accessibility features.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] While mobile browsers have similar UI features as desktop versions, the limitations of the often-smaller touch screens require mobile UIs to be simpler.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] The difference is significant for users accustomed to keyboard shortcuts.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Responsive web design is used to create websites that offer a consistent experience across the desktop and mobile versions of the website and across varying screen sizes.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] The most popular desktop browsers also have sophisticated web development tools.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Access to some web content — particularly streaming services like Netflix, Disney+, and Spotify — is restricted by Digital Rights Management (DRM) software.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] A web browser is able to access DRM-restricted content through the use of a Content Decryption Module (CDM) such as Widevine.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] As of 2020, the CDMs used by dominant web browsers require browser providers to pay costly license fees, making it unfeasible for most independent open-source browsers to offer access to DRM-restricted content.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Google Chrome has been the dominant browser worldwide since the mid-2010s and currently has a 69% global market share on all devices.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] The other two browsers in the top four are made from different codebases.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Safari, based on Apple's WebKit code, is the second most popular web browser and is dominant on Apple devices, resulting in a 16% global share.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Firefox, in fourth place, with about 2% market share, is based on Mozilla's code.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Both of these codebases are open-source, so a number of small niche browsers are also made from them.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Prior to late 2016, the majority of web traffic came from desktop computers.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] However, since then, mobile devices (smartphones) have represented the majority of web traffic.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] As of February 2025, mobile devices represent a 62% share of Internet traffic, followed by desktop at 36% and tablet at 2%.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Web browsers are popular targets for hackers, who exploit security holes to steal information, destroy files, and partake in other malicious activities.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Browser vendors regularly patch these security holes, so users are strongly encouraged to keep their browser software updated.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Other protection measures are antivirus software and being aware of scams.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] During the course of browsing, cookies received from various websites are stored by the browser.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Some of them contain login credentials or site preferences.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] However, others are used for tracking user behavior over long periods of time, so browsers typically provide a section in the menu for deleting cookies.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Some browsers have more proactive protection against cookies and trackers that limit their functionality and ability to track user behaviour.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Finer-grained management of cookies usually requires a browser extension.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Telemetry data is collected by most popular web browsers, which can usually be opted out of by the user.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] A study from 2020 portrays that there are two tiers of browsers in terms of privacy: the privacy-focused ones (Brave, DuckDuckGo, LibreWolf, Tor,Mullvad, Helium and Firefox-Focus) perform better than popular ones (Chrome, Firefox, and Safari) and recommend the first ones.
[src:bokeh-viz/web-browser] Blocking fingerprinting, cookies, tracking scripts, ads, etc. seems to explain that difference.
